Mabou Mines Archive

Contents

Series I: Correspondence

Scope and Contents note

Contains documentation of the formation of the company and its early history, fan mail and other matters. Of particular interest are letters between the playwright Samuel Beckett and company members. The series also includes correspondence with Ellen Stewart, artistic director of LaMaMa E.T.C.

Subseries A: Correspondence with individuals

Scope and Contents note

Most of the contents were originally contained in a brown accordion file folder with alphabetical tabs.

Series II: Programs

Scope and Contents note

This series comprises the original programs for performances of most of Mabou Mines' productions, and several Mabou Mines-related productions. Series II is arranged alphabetically by production and then chronologically by performance. In general, if a program lists more than one production, the first-billed production is given precedence. Additional programs and program production elements (descriptions, cast biographies, artwork, etc.) can be found in Series III and Series VIII.

31142042235799box: 6, folder: 246 (Material Type: Mixed Materials)

Series III: Production Files

Scope and Contents note

This series comprises the production files for many of Mabou Mines' stage productions; for Re-Cher-Chez and Mabou Mines/Suite, the company's studio for avant-garde performing arts, and artists-in-residence/theater-training program, respectively; and for other related productions. Materials include: correspondence (see Series IB for additional production-specific correspondence); rights and royalties agreements; artist agreements and contracts; production descriptions and summaries; research material; script elements; artist and cast biographies; programs and program production elements (see Series II); press releases, flyers, and posters; press clippings and advertisements; grant applications and other development and fund-raising material; financial records including budgets, payrolls, receipts, checks, and box-office records; touring information; technical specifications; audio specifications and cue sheets; lighting plots, cue sheets, gels, and gobos; stage plots and schematics; costume and prop design and information; and some photographs (see Series IV).
Oversize material can be found in Boxes 21, 22 and in the map case.

Series IV: Photographs

Scope and Contents note

The bulk of Series IV is comprised of professionally produced 8"x10" black-and-white prints. Other size prints, contact sheets, negatives, color snapshots, and photographers' labels make up the rest of Series IV. Most prints and contact sheets are clearly marked with the photographer's name. For each folder in Series IV the photographer is listed directly below the name of the production, where applicable. Some folders contain the work of two or more photographers. In these folders the (un-labeled) negatives were rehoused in plastic sleeves, and the original labeled sleeve was retained and placed behind the negative. Oversize photographs are housed in Box 31. See Series IA, Box 2, Folder 82 for correspondence between Mabou Mines, photographers, and photo shops. Series III also contains some photographs.

Subseries A: Production photographs

Scope and Contents note

Documentary photographs of many Mabou Mines productions. Series is arranged alphabetically by production. Within each production the original order established by Mabou Mines was retained. Generally, this means the work of individual photographers is grouped, and prints usually appear before negatives or contact sheets. There is a semblance of chronology, though many photographs are undated.

Series V: Slides

Scope and Contents note

Series V comprises several hundred slides, some documentary, some actual production elements. The slides were originally housed in either plastic sleeves grouped in three-ring binders, or plastic or cardboard slide boxes. The original labeling on these housings was faithfully transcribed.

Series VI: Scripts

Scope and Contents note

Scripts, drafts, notes, film treatments, and screenplays representing a majority of Mabou Mines' productions, and some Mabou Mines-affiliated productions. Of particular interest are the many drafts and early versions of Lee Breuer's works, scripts notated by Ruth Maleczech, and a monologue written by Samuel Beckett for David Warrilow.

Series VII: Production Books

Scope and Contents note

Series VII is made up of the contents of binders and folders that variously comprised scripts, notes, cues, contact sheets, schedules, and the like, usually heavily annotated, often compiled by a stage manager or director, for use during production of a play. Several Mabou Mines' productions, and some Mabou Mines-affiliated productions, are represented. Some folders contain scripts the company did not file with those scripts that make up Series VI. There is also significant overlap with Series III: Production Files. Of particular interest are the contents of binders used by JoAnne Akalaitis during production of the Dead End Kids film.

Series VIII: Touring Files

Scope and Contents note

This series comprises records of Mabou Mines performances outside of New York City, including multi-state and international tours. The bulk of the series spans the 1980s into the early 1990s.
Subseries A contains files relating to specific performances or tours of specific productions. Cold Harbor is especially well-represented here, as this production toured extensively in the mid-1980s. Most of the folders in Subseries A contain some combination of the following materials: correspondence with representatives of a venue; tour schedules and itineraries; contact information of cast, crew, and venue; financial records including budgets; contracts; programs and flyers; lighting plots, track sheets, and cues; ground plans and stage schematics of various venues; maps and other travel information. The folders are arranged chronologically by performance date. The files within each folder may date to several months before and/or after the performance date. This arrangement clearly shows that it was not unusual for several Mabou Mines productions to tour simultaneously. There is significant overlap with the materials in Series III: Production Files, and this subseries can be compared with Series II: Programs for a more complete record of Mabou Mines performances.
Subseries B, General Touring Files, comprises similar material (correspondence, financial records, technical specifications, etc) related to no production in particular, or related to many different productions. This series is rich in what the company called "touring inquiries." Subseries C contains information on travel discounts including airline miles programs, and information on travel and lodging in specific cities. Subseries D contains Mabou Mines' collection of information on various national and international theater organizations and festivals, some in which Mabou Mines took part. These folders are arranged in alphabetical order by organization, then by festival.

Subseries A: Touring Files by Production

Series IX: Video Recordings

Scope and Contents note

Video recordings of complete Mabou Mines productions, unless otherwise noted.

Subseries A: Video Recordings - Access Copies

Scope and Contents note

Subseries contains all researcher access copies of video material. Titles are arranged alphabetically.

Conditions Governing Access

Access copies for some materials are available by appointment for reading room viewing and listening only. Please contact fales.library@nyu.edu, 212-998-2596.

Series X: Press

Scope and Contents note

Series X contains numerous published articles written about Mabou Mines. There are original newspaper clippings, photocopies of clippings, magazine and journal articles, press releases, production histories, programs, and other related material. The material is arranged chronologically by subject. The series is divided into three subseries. The first part of Subseries A comprises pieces written about Mthe abou Mines company generally, and the second half comprises press about the company's awards and nominations. Subseries B is made up of press about individual company members and associates. The members are listed first, alphabetically, followed by the associates. Subseries C, the bulk of Series X, contains press and other material related to Mabou Mines productions and productions associated with Mabou Mines. The Mabou Mines plays are listed first, alphabetically by title, followed by the related productions.

When the collection was maintained by Mabou Mines, the newspaper reviews for some productions had been individually foldered and each given a rating based on its favorability. This rating system was expressed through the use of color-coded circle stickers attached to the tops of some folders. Rave reviews were given red or orange stickers, yellow stickers were for mixed reviews, and black were for negative reviews. Presumably, this enabled those working at Mabou Mines to quickly determine the general critical opinion of a given performance, and also served as a shortcut to finding reviews from which to pull quotes for press releases, advertisements, etc. This rating system was not retained when the collection was processed at Fales Library for the following reasons: (1) the researcher is better served if several reviews of a performance are collected into a single folder; (2) the rating system was not uniformly applied; (3) some colored stickers had fallen off before the series was processed; (4) a reader can distinguish a rave from a pan.

Subseries A: General Press

Scope and Contents note

Articles and clippings about Mabou Mines generally are listed first, followed by published mentions of the company's many awards and nominations.

Subseries C: Productions

Scope and Contents note

Articles and clippings about Mabou Mines productions are listed first, arranged alphabetically by title, then chronologically. Articles and other material about Mabou Mines-related productions are listed next. The designation "Beckett Plays" refers to any combination of Come and Go, The Lost Ones, and Play, which were often performed together in the company's early days. The company used this designation for the numerous published items that mention one or all of these plays, and it was retained for this series. Please note, however, that in other series each production is referred to by its individual title.

Series XII: Financial Files, Grants, and Development

Scope and Content note

According to the existing arrangement of material, general financial files and grant material are chronologically ordered. Development files, however, were received in alphabetical order. The original arrangement has been preserved.

Distinctions between Financial Files, Grants and Development were provided originally by the company and have been upheld. Much of the content, however, defies strict differentiation. For example, some grant-related material may be found in a box labelled "Financial Files" or some general development papers may be found in "Grants."

Series XVI. Posters

Dates:
1974-1992

Scope and Contents

This series consists of 108 posters from the Mabou Mines theater group, the majority of which are offset litho prints with a small number of electrostatic prints and photostats. Some posters show original mockup art with ink and graphite on board or with a thin tracing overlay. Posters are for performances of multiple Mabou Mines productions from the 1970s through the 1990s.
